  "dateModified": "2026-04-04",
  "datePublished": "2026-04-04",
  "description": "A trained language model is a closure fixed point: an element of a poset that is stable under further application of the training operator. LLM training stages form a sequence of increasingly constrained closure operators, each adding an additional constraint without rebuilding from scratch.\n¶Model weights as fixed points A language model\u0026rsquo;s weights represent a stable equilibrium under the training process. Once pre-training converges, reapplying the same training process to the same data produces negligible change. This is precisely what a closure fixed point is: an element WW such that applying the closure operator again yields c(W)≈Wc(W) \\approx W.\n",
